	<main>
		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="tortoise face" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-tortoise-migrations-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Galapagos giant tortoises sustain entire ecosystems with their movements. On Santa Cruz, the Ecuadorian archipelago’s most populous island, roadblocks now threaten to halt millennia of tortoise migration. Photo by Joshua Vela-Fonseca</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Slow-Motion Destruction of Tortoises’ Slow-Motion Migration</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">On the Galapagos’ most developed island, researchers are tracking a growing threat to the millennia-old migration routes of giant tortoises.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/kevin-gepford/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Kevin Gepford</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						October 22, 2024 | 1,900 words, about 9 minutes
					</aside>

					
